Source: Chatham House, The US capture of President Nicolás Maduro - and attacks on Venezuela - have no justification in international law. Author on page: Marc Weller, Director, Global Governance and Security Centre, International Law Programme, Chatham House. Published Jan. 4, 2026; updated Jan. 6, 2026. URL: https://www.chathamhouse.org/2026/01/us-capture-president-nicolas-maduro-and-attacks-venezuela-have-no-justification

Extracted relevant page text:
- The page states that the capture of Venezuelan President Nicolás Maduro and his wife by U.S. forces operating in Venezuela, and his forced transfer to the U.S. for trial, poses a significant challenge for international law.
- It states the United States described the operation as a judicial extraction mission undertaken by law enforcement operatives supported by the military.
- Chatham House states that this was a military operation of considerable scale involving strikes on military targets in and around Caracas, the capital, and the forcible abduction of a sitting president by U.S. special forces.
- It calls the operation a significant violation of Venezuelan sovereignty and the UN Charter.
- It states this is compounded by President Trump's Jan. 3 press-conference announcement that the United States will run Venezuela and administer a political transition or regime change under threat of further, more massive uses of force.
- It also states there seems to be a determination to use the threat of force to extract funds and resources in compensation for supposed stolen or nationalized U.S. assets and oil.
- It states there is no UN Security Council mandate authorizing force and that this was not U.S. self-defense triggered by a prior or ongoing armed attack by Venezuela.